DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(89)90013-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387889900138
AB  - Whether economies of scale are the major factor underlying concentration of agricultural land in large farms has long been under debate. The case study of Japanese agriculture for the past three decades confirmed the tendency observed from international comparison that increasing returns in agricultural production emerge when economic development reaches a stage at which real wage rates begin to rise sharply. It was found that the effect of scale economies was highly significant, even though the intersectoral labor market effect was greater on land concentration. The results imply that developing countries need not worry about mechanization to cause more unequal land distribution, if factor markets are not unduly distorted.
